}{\plain \fs24 \tab Originally, according to Collingwood, MS XI was  an envelope containing collected loose \softline
papers, including poems; fair-copied by the author as presents, chiefly to his father; or copied by others  \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \ul Works}{\plain \fs24  2:534). By the time the second volume of the Library Edition was published (1903), the  loose \softline
papers,   together with some others,  had been  bound up in a volume of letters and poems, 1827-44  \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \ul Works}{\plain \fs24  2:534). This binding, according to the date stamped on the spine of five other blue morrocco \softline
volumes, was done in 1889. Since Collingwood{\u8217\'92}s }{\plain \fs24 \ul Poems}{\plain \fs24  was published in 1891, the letters cannot \softline
have lain loose in an  envelope  for very long after he described MS XI.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Why, then, is the volume of the early letters stamped on the spine as bound in 1924? According \softline
to the bibliography volume (1912) of the Library Edition, when the }{\plain \fs24 \ul Works}{\plain \fs24  were completed, there were  \softline
at Brantwood some seven bound quarto volumes of letters from Ruskin to his parents,  of which the \softline
first was the 1827-44 volume described in the second volume. When the volumes of letters were sold \softline
at Sotheby{\u8217\'92}s on 24 July 1930, however, Lot 110 consisted of only six volumes. The discrepancy is \softline
explained, if rather obscurely, by a  NOTE  on a front endpaper of the present first volume.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 In the Library Edition of Ruskin (Vol. 38. p. 205) the contents of this volume are catalogued as two \softline
volumes, viz. (i) 1827-1844 and (iii) 1847-1851. This is because at the time of the catalogue the \softline
volumes were separately bound together in one volume.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab The lettes of 1859 at the end of this volume should have been placed in the volume more \softline
appropriate to their date, but were overlooked when that volume was bound.\par
}{\plain \fs24 December, 1924.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 In 1924 it was decided to disassemble the bindings of the original first and third volumes and rebind \softline
them together. This is apparently all that is meant by the awkward phrase  separately bound together in \softline
one volume.  The redisposition of the volumes{\u8217\'92} contents is clarified by comparing the bibliography list of \softline
1912 with what is stamped on the spines of the volumes currently at Yale (the bindings were never \softline
stamped with volume numbers but only with the dates of their contents):\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 1912 (}{\plain \fs24 \ul Works}{\plain \fs24 , 38:205)\ul0 \tab      1924 and afterward\par
}{\plain \fs24 vol. 1: 1827-44       vol. 1: 1827-44, 1847-51, 1859 (bd. 1924)\par
}{\plain \fs24 vol. 2: 1845     vol. 2: 1845-50 (bd. 1889)\par
}{\plain \fs24 vol. 3: 1847-48-49-50-51\ul0 \tab \par
}{\plain \fs24 vol. 4: 1851-52      vol. 3: 1851-52 (bd. 1889)\par
}{\plain \fs24 vol. 5: 1853    vol. 4: 1853 (bd. 1889)\par
