}{\plain \fs24 vol. 7: 1862-63      vol. 6: 1862-63 (bd. 1889)\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 First, it is clear that the present first volume holds the original volumes 1 and 3, as well as 1859 letters \softline
that apparently had never been bound prior to 1924. This disposition is confirmed by the volume still \softline
containing a typescript table of contents for the 1827-44 letters and poems, a typescript that differs \softline
markedly from a handwritten table of contents for the 1847-51 letters and from a page divider (no table 
of contents) for 1859. Presumably, the typescript and holograph tables of contents date from their \softline
original respective volumes.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab As for the other slight discrepancies between the two lists, they seem unlikely to have arisen \softline
from any actual redisposition of the contents of the original volumes 2 and 4-7 after 1889. Regarding \softline
volume 2, the Library Edition list fails to mention letters after 1845 though 1850, because, I imagine, \softline
those letters are from John James to Ruskin and not  from Ruskin to his parents  (}{\plain \fs24 \ul Works}{\plain \fs24 , 38:205)--Ruskin{\u8217\'92}s authorship apparently being the editors{\u8217\'92} primary concern at that point. The same explanation \softline
may be given for the failure of the Library Edition list to mention letters of 1867 in volume 6 (now \softline
volume 5): the 1867 letters are to Ruskin from his mother, not the reverse. Finally, the mismatch \softline
regarding that same volume{\u8217\'92}s 1857 correspondence can be explained by the Library Edition{\u8217\'92}s \softline
providing the greater accuracy, for once: that volume contains only a few 1857 letters, as compared to \softline
the much more substantial collection of 1858-61, as identified on the spine.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Only the first of the blue morrocco volumes, of course, should be identified as MS XI--and, \softline
strictly, only the 1827-44 section of that volume, as presently bound. Although we can never know \softline
precisely what was contained in Collingwood{\u8217\'92}s  envelope,  nothing appears to have been lost since \softline
Cook and Wedderburn described the first binding of these letters (see }{\plain \fs24 \ul Works}{\plain \fs24  2:534, although this list \softline
omits prose letters). Moreover, assuming the typescript table of contents for the 1827-44 section to be \softline
the original, one finds it to correspond to all manuscripts presently extant in that section. The 1827-44 \softline
letters and poems form a core source for }{\plain \fs24 \ul RFL}{\plain \fs24 , where the present blue morrocco volume 1 is called  \softline
RMS I. \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab It may be mentioned here that the 1924 rebinding of the original volumes 1 and 3 matches the \softline
1889 bindings. The five 1889 bindings are all the same blue morrocco, gilt, and decorated (only more \softline
